rComments: This course taught me how to write papers (that will be graded well) at a university level: by focusing on major theories and incorporating them. No textbook, just free readings, but you have to read them(or at least skim)to do well. Shelagh is happy to explain assignments in detail (repeatedly)and give extensions, pretty easy marker too.

I really did enjoy her course. It is true that she speaks way too fast but her lectures are very interesting. She is very motivated and knows what she is teaching. She gives great feedback and she is always there when you need help. I would totally recommend her and advice future students to go to her office hours if you have trouble understanding

Very difficult to follow along and take notes, especially since we're not allowed laptops, speaks WAY too quietly even with the microphone, cannot use BBL to save her life She needs to learn how to teach a class, because knowing the content isn't important if you can't teach it to others

She's a great prof. Prof Roxburgh expects critical analysis of the topics she presents, which is political science for you. You're only expected to know basic points from the readings so you can skim over them. The exams are essays & YOUR analysis not what the authors say. It's not a hard class to do well in if you put the work in.

Overall, not a very good professor: readings are too dense for a second year course (and the readings are easily 75 pages a week), no textbook so you have to find the readings yourself online, bans laptops and just reads from her notes (good luck keeping up with what she says). Try to avoid having her, if possible.
